g h6 ">
                <div class=3D"post__content wysiwyg p theme__anchors--under=
line"><h2>Quantized Academy</h2>
<p>Patrick Honner, a nationally recognized high school teacher from Brookly=
n, New York, introduces basic concepts from the latest mathematical researc=
h.</p>
<hr>
<p><a href=3D"https://www.quantamagazine.org/tag/quantized-academy/">See al=
l&nbsp;Quantized Academy Columns</a></p>
</div>
            </div>
        </aside>
       =20
<p>The infamous Collatz conjecture says that if you start with any positive=
 integer, you=E2=80=99ll always end up in this loop. And you=E2=80=99ll pro=
bably ignore my warning about trying to solve it: It just seems too simple =
and too orderly to resist understanding. In fact, it would be hard to find =
a mathematician who hasn=E2=80=99t played around with this problem.</p>
<p>I couldn=E2=80=99t ignore it when I first learned of it in school. My fr=
iends and I spent days trading thrilling insights that never seemed to get =
us any closer to an answer. But the Collatz conjecture is infamous for a re=
ason: Even though every number that=E2=80=99s ever been tried ends up in th=
at loop, we=E2=80=99re still not sure it=E2=80=99s always true. Despite all=
 the attention, it=E2=80=99s still just a conjecture.</p>
<p>Yet progress has been made. One of the world=E2=80=99s greatest living m=
athematicians ignored all the warnings and <a href=3D"https://www.quantamag=
azine.org/mathematician-terence-tao-and-the-collatz-conjecture-20191211/">t=
ook a crack at it</a>, making the biggest strides on the problem in decades=
. Let=E2=80=99s take a look at what makes this simple problem so very compl=
icated.</p>
<p>To understand the Collatz conjecture, we=E2=80=99ll start with the follo=
wing function:</p>
<p style=3D"text-align: center;"><span class=3D"MathJax_Preview"> f(n) =3D =
\begin{cases}=20
n / 2 &amp; \text{if $n$ is even } \\=20
3n+1 &amp; \text{if $n$ is odd }=20
\end{cases}\ </span></p>
<p>You might remember =E2=80=9Cpiecewise=E2=80=9D functions from school: Th=
e above function takes an input&nbsp;<em>n</em>&nbsp;and applies one of two=
 rules to it, depending on whether the input is odd or even. This function&=
nbsp;<em>f&nbsp;</em>enacts the rules of the procedure we described above: =
For example,&nbsp;<em>f</em>&nbsp;(10) =3D 10/2 =3D 5 since 10 is even, and=
&nbsp;<em>f</em>&nbsp;(5) =3D 3 =C3=97 5 + 1 =3D 16 since 5 is odd.&nbsp;Be=
cause of the rule for odd inputs, the Collatz conjecture is also known as t=
he 3<em>n</em> + 1 conjecture.</p>
<p>The Collatz conjecture deals with =E2=80=9Corbits=E2=80=9D of this funct=
ion&nbsp;<em>f</em>.&nbsp;An orbit is what you get if you start with a numb=
er and apply a function repeatedly, taking each output and feeding it back =
into the function as a new input. We call this =E2=80=9Citerating=E2=80=9D =
the function. We=E2=80=99ve already started computing the orbit of 10 under=
&nbsp;<em>f</em>,&nbsp;&nbsp;so let=E2=80=99s find the next few terms:</p>
<p style=3D"text-align: center;"><em>f&nbsp;</em>(10) =3D 10/2 =3D 5<br>
<em>f&nbsp;</em>(5) =3D 3 =C3=97 5 + 1 =3D 16<br>
<em>f&nbsp;</em>(16) =3D 16/2 =3D 8<br>
<em>f&nbsp;</em>(8) =3D 8/2 =3D 4</p>
<p style=3D"text-align: left;">A convenient way to represent an orbit is as=
 a sequence with arrows. Here=E2=80=99s the orbit of 10 under&nbsp;<em>f</e=
m>:</p>
<p style=3D"text-align: center;">10 =E2=86=92 5 =E2=86=92 16 =E2=86=92 8 =
=E2=86=92 4 =E2=86=92 2 =E2=86=92 1 =E2=86=92 4 =E2=86=92 2 =E2=86=92 1 =E2=
=86=92 =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"text-align: left;">At the end we see we are stuck in the loop&n=
bsp;1 =E2=86=92 4 =E2=86=92 2 =E2=86=92 1 =E2=86=92 =E2=80=A6.</p>
<p style=3D"text-align: left;">Similarly, the orbit for 11 under&nbsp;<em>f=
&nbsp;</em>can be represented as</p>
<p style=3D"text-align: center;">11 =E2=86=92 34 =E2=86=92 17 =E2=86=92 52 =
=E2=86=92 26 =E2=86=92 13 =E2=86=92 40 =E2=86=92 20 =E2=86=92 10 =E2=86=92 =
5 =E2=86=92 16 =E2=86=92 8 =E2=86=92 4 =E2=86=92 2 =E2=86=92 1 =E2=86=92 4 =
=E2=86=92&nbsp;=E2=80=A6.</p>
<p style=3D"text-align: left;">Again we end up in that same loop. Try a few=
 more examples and you=E2=80=99ll see that the orbit always seems to stabil=
ize in that 4 =E2=86=92 2 =E2=86=92 1 =E2=86=92 =E2=80=A6&nbsp;loop. The st=
arting values of 9 and 19 are fun, and if you=E2=80=99ve got a few minutes =
to spare, try 27. If your arithmetic is right, you=E2=80=99ll get there aft=
er 111 steps.</p>
<p>The Collatz conjecture states that the orbit of every number under&nbsp;=
<em>f </em>eventually reaches 1. And while no one has proved the conjecture=
, it has been verified for every number less than 2<sup>68</sup>.&nbsp;So i=
f you=E2=80=99re looking for a counterexample, you can start around 300 qui=
ntillion. (You were warned!)</p>
<p>It=E2=80=99s easy to verify that the Collatz conjecture is true for any =
particular number: Just compute the orbit until you arrive at 1. But to see=
 why it=E2=80=99s hard to prove for every number, let=E2=80=99s explore a s=
lightly simpler function,<em>=E2=84=8A</em>.</p>
<p style=3D"text-align: center;"><span class=3D"MathJax_Preview"> g(n) =3D =
\begin{cases}=20
n / 2 &amp; \text{if $n$ is even } \\=20
n+1 &amp; \text{if $n$ is odd }=20
\end{cases}\ </span></p>
<p style=3D"text-align: left;">The function<em>=E2=84=8A&nbsp;</em>is simil=
ar to&nbsp;<em>f</em>, but for odd numbers it just adds 1 instead of tripli=
ng them first. Since&nbsp;<em>=E2=84=8A</em> and&nbsp;<em>f</em> are differ=
ent functions, numbers have different orbits under&nbsp;<em>=E2=84=8A&nbsp;=
</em>than under&nbsp;<em>f</em>. For example, here are the orbits of 10 and=
 11 under&nbsp;<em>=E2=84=8A</em>:</p>
<p style=3D"text-align: center;">10 =E2=86=92 5 =E2=86=92 6 =E2=86=92 3 =E2=
=86=92 4 =E2=86=92 2 =E2=86=92 1 =E2=86=92 2 =E2=86=92 1 =E2=86=92 2 =E2=86=
=92 =E2=80=A6<br>
11 =E2=86=92 12 =E2=86=92 6 =E2=86=92 3 =E2=86=92 4 =E2=86=92 2 =E2=86=92 1=
 =E2=86=92 2 =E2=86=92 1=E2=86=92 2 =E2=86=92 =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"text-align: left;">Notice that the orbit of 11 reaches 1 faster=
 under&nbsp;<em>=E2=84=8A&nbsp;</em>than under&nbsp;<em>f</em>. The orbit o=
f 27 also reaches 1 much faster under&nbsp;<em>=E2=84=8A.</em></p>
<p style=3D"text-align: center;">27 =E2=86=92 28 =E2=86=92 14 =E2=86=92 7 =
=E2=86=92 8 =E2=86=92 4 =E2=86=92 2 =E2=86=92 1 =E2=86=92 2 =E2=86=92&nbsp;=
=E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"text-align: left;">In these examples, orbits under&nbsp;<em>=E2=
=84=8A&nbsp;</em>appear to stabilize, just like orbits under&nbsp;<em>f</em=
>, but in a slightly simpler loop:</p>
<p style=3D"text-align: center;">=E2=86=92 2 =E2=86=92 1 =E2=86=92 2 =E2=86=
=92 1 =E2=86=92&nbsp;=E2=80=A6.</p>
<p style=3D"text-align: left;">We might conjecture that orbits under<em>=E2=
=84=8A&nbsp;</em>always get to 1. I=E2=80=99ll call this the =E2=80=9CNolla=
tz=E2=80=9D conjecture, but we could also call it the&nbsp;<em>n</em> + 1 c=
onjecture. We could explore this by testing more orbits, but knowing someth=
ing is true for a bunch of numbers =E2=80=94 even&nbsp;2<sup>68&nbsp;</sup>=
of them =E2=80=94 isn=E2=80=99t a proof that it=E2=80=99s true for every nu=
mber. Fortunately, the Nollatz conjecture can actually be proved. Here=E2=
=80=99s how.</p>
<p style=3D"text-align: left;">First, we know that half of a positive integ=
er is always less than the integer itself. So if&nbsp;<em>n&nbsp;</em>is ev=
en and positive, then&nbsp;<em>=E2=84=8A</em>(<em>n</em>) =3D<em>&nbsp;n</e=
m>/2 &lt;<em>&nbsp;n.&nbsp;</em>In other words, when an orbit reaches an ev=
en number, the next number will always be smaller.</p>
<p style=3D"text-align: left;">Now, if&nbsp;<em>n</em>&nbsp;is odd, then&nb=
sp;<em>=E2=84=8A</em>(<em>n</em>) =3D<em>&nbsp;n&nbsp;</em>+ 1 which is big=
ger than&nbsp;<em>n</em>. But since&nbsp;<em>n</em>&nbsp;is odd,&nbsp;<em>n=
&nbsp;</em>+ 1 is even, and so we know where the orbit goes next:&nbsp;<em>=
=E2=84=8A&nbsp;</em>will cut&nbsp;<em>n&nbsp;</em>+ 1 in half. For an odd&n=
bsp;<em>n&nbsp;</em>the orbit will look like this:</p>
<p style=3D"text-align: center;">=E2=80=A6 =E2=86=92&nbsp;<em>n&nbsp;</em>=
=E2=86=92&nbsp;<em>n&nbsp;</em>+ 1 =E2=86=92 <span class=3D"MathJax_Preview=
"> \frac{n+1}{2}</span> =E2=86=92 =E2=80=A6</p>
<p>Notice that <span class=3D"MathJax_Preview"> \frac{n+1}{2}</span> =3D <s=
pan class=3D"MathJax_Preview"> \frac{n}{2}</span> + <span class=3D"MathJax_=
Preview"> \frac{1}{2}</span>. Since <span class=3D"MathJax_Preview"> \frac{=
n}{2}</span> &lt;&nbsp;<em>n&nbsp;</em>and <span class=3D"MathJax_Preview">=
 \frac{1}{2}</span> is small, <span class=3D"MathJax_Preview"> \frac{n}{2}<=
/span> + <span class=3D"MathJax_Preview"> \frac{1}{2}</span> is probably al=
so less than&nbsp;<em>n</em>. In fact, some simple number theory can show u=
s that as long as&nbsp;<em>n</em>&nbsp;&gt; 1, then it=E2=80=99s always tru=
e that <span class=3D"MathJax_Preview"> \frac{n}{2}</span> + <span class=3D=
"MathJax_Preview"> \frac{1}{2}</span>&lt;&nbsp;<em>n</em>.</p>
<p>This tells us that when an orbit under&nbsp;<em>=E2=84=8A&nbsp;</em>reac=
hes an odd number greater than 1, we=E2=80=99ll always be at a smaller numb=
er two steps later. And now we can outline a proof of the Nollatz conjectur=
e: Anywhere in our orbit, whether at an even or an odd number, we=E2=80=99l=
l trend downward. The only exception is when we hit 1 at the bottom of our =
descent. But once we hit 1 we=E2=80=99re trapped the loop, just as we conje=
ctured.</p>
<p>Can a similar argument work for the Collatz conjecture? Let=E2=80=99s go=
 back to the original function.</p>
<p style=3D"text-align: center;"><span class=3D"MathJax_Preview"> f(n) =3D =
\begin{cases}=20
n / 2 &amp; \text{if $n$ is even } \\=20
3n+1 &amp; \text{if $n$ is odd }=20
\end{cases}\ </span></p>
<p>As with&nbsp;<em>=E2=84=8A</em>, applying&nbsp;<em>f</em> to an even num=
ber makes it smaller. And&nbsp;as with&nbsp;<em>=E2=84=8A</em>,&nbsp;applyi=
ng&nbsp;<em>f</em> to an odd number produces an even number, which means we=
 know what happens next:&nbsp;<em>f</em> will cut the new number in half. H=
ere=E2=80=99s what the orbit under&nbsp;<em>f&nbsp;</em>looks like when&nbs=
p;<em>n</em>&nbsp;is odd:</p>
<p style=3D"text-align: center;">=E2=80=A6 =E2=86=92&nbsp;<em>n&nbsp;</em>=
=E2=86=92 3<em>n&nbsp;</em>+ 1 =E2=86=92 <span class=3D"MathJax_Preview"> \=
frac{3n+1}{2}</span> =E2=86=92 =E2=80=A6</p>
<p>But here=E2=80=99s where our argument falls apart. Unlike our example ab=
ove, this number is bigger than&nbsp;<em>n</em>: <span class=3D"MathJax_Pre=
view"> \frac{3n+1}{2}</span> =3D <span class=3D"MathJax_Preview"> \frac{3n}=
{2}</span> + <span class=3D"MathJax_Preview"> \frac{1}{2}</span>, and <span=
 class=3D"MathJax_Preview"> \frac{3n}{2}</span> =3D 1.5<em>n</em>, which is=
 always bigger than&nbsp;<em>n</em>.&nbsp;The key to our proof of the Nolla=
tz conjecture was that an odd number must end up smaller two steps later, b=
ut this isn=E2=80=99t true in the Collatz case. Our argument won=E2=80=99t =
work.</p>
<p>If you=E2=80=99re like me and my friends back in school, you might now b=
e excited about proving that the Collatz conjecture is false: After all, if=
 the orbit keeps getting bigger, then how can it get down to 1? But that ar=
gument requires thinking about what happens next, and what happens next ill=
uminates why the Collatz conjecture is so slippery: We can=E2=80=99t be sur=
e whether&nbsp;<span class=3D"MathJax_Preview"> \frac{3n+1}{2}</span>&nbsp;=
is even or odd.</p>
<p>We know that&nbsp;3<em>n&nbsp;</em>+ 1&nbsp;is even. If&nbsp;3<em>n&nbsp=
;</em>+ 1 is also divisible by 4, then&nbsp;<span class=3D"MathJax_Preview"=
> \frac{3n+1}{2}</span>&nbsp;is also even, and the orbit will fall. But if&=
nbsp;3<em>n&nbsp;</em>+ 1&nbsp;is not divisible by 4, then&nbsp;<span class=
=3D"MathJax_Preview"> \frac{3n+1}{2}</span>&nbsp;is odd, and the orbit will=
 rise. In general we can=E2=80=99t predict which will be true, so our argum=
ent stalls out.</p>
<p>But this approach isn=E2=80=99t completely useless. Since half of all po=
sitive integers are even, there=E2=80=99s a 50% chance that&nbsp;<span clas=
s=3D"MathJax_Preview"> \frac{3n+1}{2}</span> is even, which makes the next =
step in the orbit&nbsp;<span class=3D"MathJax_Preview"> \frac{3n+1}{4}</spa=
n>.&nbsp;For&nbsp;<em>n</em>&nbsp;&gt; 1&nbsp;this is less than&nbsp;<em>n&=
nbsp;</em>,&nbsp;so half the time an odd number should get lower after two =
steps. There=E2=80=99s also a 50% chance that&nbsp;<span class=3D"MathJax_P=
review"> \frac{3n+1}{4}</span>&nbsp;is even, which means there=E2=80=99s a =
25% chance that an odd number will be reduced to less than half of where it=
 started after three steps. And so on. The net result is that, in some aver=
age way, Collatz orbits decrease when they encounter an odd number. And sin=
ce Collatz orbits always decrease at even numbers, this suggests that all C=
ollatz sequences must decrease in the long run. This probabilistic argument=
 is widely known, but no one has been able to extend it to a complete proof=
 of the conjecture.</p>
<p>Yet several mathematicians have proved that the Collatz conjecture is =
=E2=80=9Calmost always=E2=80=9D true. This means they=E2=80=99ve proved tha=
t, relative to the amount of numbers they know lead to 1, the amount of num=
bers they aren=E2=80=99t sure about is negligible. In 1976 the Estonian Ame=
rican mathematician Riho Terras <a href=3D"http://matwbn.icm.edu.pl/ksiazki=
/aa/aa30/aa3034.pdf" target=3D"_blank">proved<span class=3D"screen-reader-t=
ext"> (opens a new tab)</span></a> that, after repeated application of the =
Collatz function, almost all numbers eventually wind up lower than where th=
ey started. As we saw above, showing that the numbers in the orbit consiste=
ntly get smaller is one path to showing that they eventually get to 1.</p>
