n</em>, Tao proved that for almost all numbers the Collatz sequence of <em>=
n</em> ends up much lower: below&nbsp;<span class=3D"MathJax_Preview"> \fra=
c{n}{2}</span>,&nbsp;below&nbsp;<span class=3D"MathJax_Preview">&nbsp;\sqrt=
{n}</span>,&nbsp;below <span class=3D"MathJax_Preview"> \ln n</span> (the n=
atural log of <em>n</em>), even below every&nbsp;<em><span id=3D"MathJax-Sp=
an-140" class=3D"mi">f</span></em><span id=3D"MathJax-Span-141" class=3D"mo=
">(</span><em><span id=3D"MathJax-Span-142" class=3D"mi">n</span></em><span=
 class=3D"mo">) where&nbsp;<em><span id=3D"MathJax-Span-140" class=3D"mi">f=
</span></em><span id=3D"MathJax-Span-141" class=3D"mo">(</span><em><span id=
=3D"MathJax-Span-142" class=3D"mi">x</span></em>)&nbsp;</span>is any functi=
on that goes off to infinity, no matter how slowly. That is, for almost eve=
ry number, we can guarantee that its Collatz sequence goes as low as we wan=
t. In a <a href=3D"https://terrytao.files.wordpress.com/2020/02/collatz.pdf=
" target=3D"_blank">talk about the problem<span class=3D"screen-reader-text=
"> (opens a new tab)</span></a>, Tao said this result is =E2=80=9Cabout as =
close as one can get to the Collatz conjecture without actually solving it.=
=E2=80=9D</p>
<p>Even so, the conjecture will continue to attract mathematicians and enth=
usiasts. So pick a number, any number, and give it a go. Just remember, you=
=E2=80=99ve been warned: Don=E2=80=99t get stuck in an endless loop.</p>
<h2>Exercises</h2>
<p style=3D"padding-left: 0px;">1. Show that there are infinitely many numb=
ers whose Collatz orbits pass through 1.</p>
<p style=3D"padding-left: 0px;">2. The =E2=80=9Cstopping time=E2=80=9D of a=
 number <em>n</em> is the smallest number of steps it takes for the Collatz=
 orbit of <em>n</em> to reach 1. For example, the stopping time of 10 is 6,=
 and the stopping time of 11 is 14. Find two numbers with stopping time 5.<=
/p>
<p style=3D"padding-left: 0px;">3. In a recent talk on the Collatz conjectu=
re, Terrance Tao mentioned the following Collatz-like function:</p>
<p style=3D"text-align: center;"><span class=3D"MathJax_Preview"> h(n) =3D =
\begin{cases}=20
n / 2 &amp; \text{if $n$ is even } \\=20
3n-1 &amp; \text{if $n$ is odd }=20
\end{cases}\ </span></p>
<p style=3D"padding-left: 0px;">Tao points out that in addition to the 1 =
=E2=86=92 2 =E2=86=92 1 =E2=86=92 2 =E2=86=92 1=E2=80=A6 loop, two other lo=
ops appear. Can you find them?</p>
<h2>Answers</h2>
<div class=3D"reveal-next" style=3D"box-shadow: inset 0 0 0 rgba(0, 0, 0, 0=
), 0 1px 0 #1a1a1a; cursor: pointer; display: inline-block;">Click for Answ=
er 1:</div>
<div class=3D"revealable" style=3D"visibility: hidden;">
<p>Notice that every power of 2 has a simple orbit path to 1. For example,<=
/p>
<p>2<sup>4</sup> =E2=86=92 2<sup>3</sup> =E2=86=92 2<sup>2</sup> =E2=86=92 =
2 =E2=86=92 1 =E2=86=92 =E2=80=A6</p>
<p>Since there are infinitely many powers of 2, there are infinitely many n=
umbers whose Collatz orbits pass through 1.</p>
</div>
<div class=3D"reveal-next" style=3D"box-shadow: inset 0 0 0 rgba(0, 0, 0, 0=
), 0 1px 0 #1a1a1a; cursor: pointer; display: inline-block;">Click for Answ=
er 2:</div>
<div class=3D"revealable" style=3D"visibility: hidden;">
<p>Notice that 2<sup>5</sup> has stopping time 5, since 2<sup>5</sup> =E2=
=86=92 2<sup>4</sup> =E2=86=92 2<sup>3</sup> =E2=86=92 2<sup>2</sup> =E2=86=
=92 2 =E2=86=92 1 =E2=86=92 =E2=80=A6. And since 2<sup>4</sup> has stopping=
 time 4, any number that is one step away from 2<sup>4</sup> has stopping t=
ime 5. For example, 5 =E2=86=92 16 =E2=86=92 8 =E2=86=92 4 =E2=86=92 2 =E2=
=86=92 1. Could there be others?</p>
</div>
<div class=3D"reveal-next" style=3D"box-shadow: inset 0 0 0 rgba(0, 0, 0, 0=
), 0 1px 0 #1a1a1a; cursor: pointer; display: inline-block;">Click for Answ=
er 3:</div>
<div class=3D"revealable" style=3D"visibility: hidden;">
<p>The other loops are</p>
<p>5 =E2=86=92 14 =E2=86=92 7 =E2=86=92 20 =E2=86=92 10 =E2=86=92 5 =E2=86=
=92 =E2=80=A6</p>
<p>and</p>
<p>17 =E2=86=92 50 =E2=86=92 25 =E2=86=92 74 =E2=86=92 37 =E2=86=92 110 =E2=
=86=92 55 =E2=86=92 164 =E2=86=92 82 =E2=86=92 41 =E2=86=92 122 =E2=86=92 6=
1 =E2=86=92 182 =E2=86=92 91 =E2=86=92 272 =E2=86=92 136 =E2=86=92 68 =E2=
=86=92 34 =E2=86=92 17 =E2=86=92 =E2=80=A6.</p>
</div>
<p></p>
</div>
